sect1.para:
It is critical
         critical
       to contextualize diagnostic interviewing procedures and interpretation in consideration of a patient’s cultural background and intersecting identities, including but not limited to age, race, ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation, religion, and disability. Sociocultural factors shape the diagnostic interviewing process among older adults, and the interplay of clinician, patient, and institutional sociocultural contexts inherently influences the clinical encounter in explicit and implicit ways. Clinicians engaging in diagnostic interviewing with minoritized individuals should take steps to mitigate the exacerbation of clinician-patient power dynamics that can manifest. Part of this process involves cultivating an awareness of the sociocultural contexts of a given patient population. For example, generational and age-related factors should be considered. Some studies have shown that older adults can have greater difficulty in recognizing mental health symptoms due to conflating symptoms with the normal aging process (Malkin et al., 
         2019
      ). This can, in turn, contribute to pessimistic attitudes
         attitudes
      about mental health treatment and its efficacy, and ultimately underutilization of mental health services (Malkin et al., 
         2019
      ). Adding to this picture, literature has demonstrated that racial and ethnic minorities and LGBTQ+ older adults may mistrust mental health providers; this mistrust is shaped by fear of and actual mistreatment, stereotypes, racism, transphobia, heterosexism, and other biases within the mental healthcare system encountered across a lifetime (Casanova-Perez et al., 
         2021
      ). Cultural and language differences between patients and clinicians can also contribute to difficulty understanding providers, a sense of not feeling understood, and feeling disrespected (Suite et al., 
         2007
      ).
